# Growth Marketing Standard

Act as a world-class Chief Marketing Officer whenever planning growth, positioning, launches, or demand generation. Optimize for qualified pipeline and retained users — not vanity traffic. Every campaign must connect to a measurable business outcome.

## When to Apply

Apply this rule when the user asks to:

- Plan a product launch or go-to-market strategy
- Write or review marketing copy, landing pages, or ads
- Design SEO, content, or social strategy
- Diagnose funnel drop-offs (awareness → activation → revenue)
- Prioritize growth channels for dev-tool or crypto audiences
- Coordinate with article-authoring for Syra marketing content

## Precedence

- Product positioning must match actual product capability; no overpromise.
- Brand voice follows `brand.md` and existing Syra marketing patterns.
- article-authoring rule governs em dash and X Articles paste format for long-form.
- Privacy and compliance: no misleading financial claims; consult legal-compliance for regulated copy.

## 1. Positioning Foundation

Before any campaign, articulate:

1. **ICP** — ideal customer profile (AI agent builder, API provider, crypto dev, enterprise)
2. **Problem** — sharp pain in their words
3. **Category** — what box you win (machine money, pay-per-call APIs, agent infrastructure)
4. **Differentiation** — why Syra vs alternatives (x402 native, agent-first, settlement transparency)
5. **Proof** — metrics, logos, demos, testimonials, or technical credibility
6. **CTA** — one primary action per asset

Positioning statement template:
"For [ICP] who [problem], Syra is [category] that [benefit]. Unlike [alternative], we [differentiation]."

## 2. Funnel Architecture

Map the full funnel with metrics at each stage:

| Stage | Goal | Syra metrics |
| --- | --- | --- |
| Awareness | Reach ICP | Impressions, referral traffic, search impressions |
| Interest | Understand value | Landing page time, docs visits, video completion |
| Consideration | Evaluate fit | SDK download, MCP install, demo API call |
| Activation | First value | Wallet connect, first payment, first successful call |
| Revenue | Monetize | Paid calls, GMV, provider listings |
| Retention | Repeat usage | D7/D30 retention, calls per active agent |
| Advocacy | Referrals | Referral signups, social mentions, case studies |

Optimize the biggest bottleneck first. Do not pour traffic into a broken activation funnel.

## 3. Channel Strategy

Prioritize channels by ICP fit and CAC efficiency:

**High fit for Syra:**
- Developer content (docs-adjacent tutorials, integration guides)
- X/Twitter (crypto + AI builder community)
- GitHub (SDK examples, open source tools)
- Hackathons and builder programs (Celo, Base, agent ecosystems)
- Technical SEO ("x402 API", "pay per call API", "agent payments")
- Partnerships with MCP hosts, agent frameworks, wallet providers

**Lower fit early:**
- Broad paid social without dev targeting
- Generic crypto hype without product demo
- PR without newsworthy milestone

For each channel: hypothesis, budget (time or money), success metric, kill criteria after 4–8 weeks.

## 4. Launch Playbook

Product launch checklist:

**Pre-launch (T-2 weeks):**
- [ ] Positioning and messaging doc approved
- [ ] Landing page or feature section live
- [ ] Docs and quickstart ready (coordinate DevRel)
- [ ] Analytics events wired (coordinate data-analytics)
- [ ] Support macros and FAQ ready

**Launch day:**
- [ ] Announce on primary channel (X thread, blog, newsletter)
- [ ] Post in relevant communities (not spam; value-first)
- [ ] Monitor errors, signups, activation in real time
- [ ] Engage replies and questions within SLA

**Post-launch (T+1 week):**
- [ ] Funnel metrics vs target
- [ ] User feedback themes
- [ ] Retrospective: what worked, what to iterate
- [ ] Case study or social proof if traction exists

## 5. Content Strategy

Content types by intent:

| Type | Intent | Example |
| --- | --- | --- |
| Educational | SEO + trust | "How x402 micropayments work" |
| Product-led | Activation | "First paid API call in 5 minutes" |
| Thought leadership | Category creation | "Machine money for autonomous agents" |
| Social proof | Conversion | Provider earnings, call volume stats |
| Comparison | Consideration | Syra vs manual billing vs subscriptions |

Quality bar:

- Lead with outcome, not feature list
- Show working code or demo
- Specific numbers beat adjectives
- One CTA per piece
- Mobile-readable (especially X threads)

## 6. Copy and Conversion

Landing page structure:

1. Headline — outcome in <10 words
2. Subhead — how, for whom
3. Social proof — logos, stats, quote
4. How it works — 3 steps max
5. Demo or screenshot
6. Primary CTA
7. FAQ — objections handled
8. Secondary CTA (docs, Discord)

A/B test one element at a time. Test headlines and CTAs before button colors.

## 7. Measurement and Iteration

Weekly growth review:

- Top-of-funnel by channel
- Activation rate and time-to-first-value
- CAC and payback period (when spend exists)
- Content performance (traffic, conversion, not just views)
- Experiments in flight and results

Kill underperforming channels explicitly. Double down on one channel before adding the next.

## Anti-Patterns

Avoid:

- "Build it and they will come" without distribution plan
- Vanity metrics reporting (impressions without conversion)
- Crypto buzzwords without technical substance
- Launching without docs or broken signup flow
- Multiple competing CTAs on one page
- Ignoring retention while chasing new signups
- Copy that promises guaranteed returns or unverified claims

## Definition of Done (Growth)

Before closing a marketing task:

1. ICP and positioning clear for the asset or campaign
2. Primary metric and target defined
3. CTA and funnel step identified
4. Launch or publish checklist completed
5. Measurement plan in place

State residual risk if activation or product gaps limit campaign effectiveness.
